  • synonyms: Armenia, Republic of Armenia, Hayastan

title: asia
titlehtml: asia
contenthtml:
noun (object) Osiyo. The largest continent with 60% of the earth's population. It is joined to Europe on the west to form Eurasia. It is the site of some of the world's earliest civilizations.
  • synonyms: Asia

title: asia minor
titlehtml: asia minor
contenthtml:
noun (location) Kichik Osiyo, Onadoʻli, Anatoliya. A peninsula in southwestern Asia that forms the Asian part of Turkey.

title: atomic number 1
titlehtml: atomic number 1
contenthtml:
noun (substance) водород. A nonmetallic univalent element that is normally a colorless and odorless highly flammable diatomic gas. The simplest and lightest and most abundant element in the universe.
  • synonyms: hydrogen, H, atomic number 1
  • hypernym: chemical element, element; gas
  • substance holonym: water, H2O
  • hyponym: tritium

title: atomic number 10
titlehtml: atomic number 10
contenthtml:
noun (substance) неон. A colorless odorless gaseous element that give a red glow in a vacuum tube. One of the six inert gasses. Occurs in the air in small amounts.
  • synonyms: neon, Ne, atomic number 10
  • hypernym: chemical element, element; noble gas, inert gas, argonon
  • substance holonym: air

title: atomic number 100
titlehtml: atomic number 100
contenthtml:
noun (substance) фермий. A radioactive transuranic metallic element produced by bombarding plutonium with neutrons.
  • synonyms: fermium, Fm, atomic number 100
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal

title: atomic number 101
titlehtml: atomic number 101
contenthtml:
noun (substance) менделеевий. A radioactive transuranic element synthesized by bombarding einsteinium with alpha particles (Md is the current symbol for mendelevium but Mv was formerly the symbol).
  • synonyms: mendelevium, Md, Mv, atomic number 101
  • hypernym: chemical element, element

title: atomic number 102
titlehtml: atomic number 102
contenthtml:
noun (substance) нобелий. A radioactive transuranic element synthesized by bombarding curium with carbon ions. 7 isotopes are known.
  • synonyms: nobelium, No, atomic number 102
  • hypernym: chemical element, element

title: atomic number 103
titlehtml: atomic number 103
contenthtml:
noun (substance) лоуренсий. A radioactive transuranic element synthesized from californium.
  • synonyms: lawrencium, Lr, atomic number 103
  • hypernym: chemical element, element

title: atomic number 104
titlehtml: atomic number 104
contenthtml:
noun (substance) дубний. A radioactive transuranic element which has been synthesized.
  • synonyms: rutherfordium, Rf, unnilquadium, Unq, element 104, atomic number 104
  • hypernym: chemical element, element

title: atomic number 105
titlehtml: atomic number 105
contenthtml:
noun (substance) жолиотий. A transuranic element.
  • synonyms: dubnium, Db, hahnium, element 105, atomic number 105
  • hypernym: chemical element, element

title: atomic number 11
titlehtml: atomic number 11
contenthtml:
noun (substance) натрий. A silvery soft waxy metallic element of the alkali metal group. Occurs abundantly in natural compounds (especially in salt water). Burns with a yellow flame and reacts violently in water. Occurs in sea water and in the mineral halite (rock salt).
  • synonyms: sodium, Na, atomic number 11
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: seawater, saltwater, brine; halite, rock salt

title: atomic number 12
titlehtml: atomic number 12
contenthtml:
noun (substance) магний. A light silver-white ductile bivalent metallic element. In pure form it burns with brilliant white flame. Occurs naturally only in combination (as in magnesite and dolomite and carnallite and spinel and olivine).
  • synonyms: magnesium, Mg, atomic number 12
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: carnallite; dolomite, bitter spar; magnesite; olivine; periclase, magnesia, magnesium oxide; spinel

title: atomic number 13
titlehtml: atomic number 13
contenthtml:
noun (substance) alyuminiy, алюминий. A silvery ductile metallic element found primarily in bauxite.
  • synonyms: aluminum, aluminium, Al, atomic number 13
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: aluminum foil, aluminium foil, tin foil; bauxite; Duralumin
  • hyponym: alum, potassium alum, potash alum; alum, ammonia alum, ammonium alum

title: atomic number 15
titlehtml: atomic number 15
contenthtml:
noun (substance) fosfor, фосфор. A multivalent nonmetallic element of the nitrogen family that occurs commonly in inorganic phosphate rocks and as organic phosphates in all living cells. Is highly reactive and occurs in several allotropic forms.
  • synonyms: phosphorus, P, atomic number 15
  • hypernym: chemical element, element
  • substance holonym: apatite

title: atomic number 16
titlehtml: atomic number 16
contenthtml:
noun (substance) олтингугурт. An abundant tasteless odorless multivalent nonmetallic element. Best known in yellow crystals. Occurs in many sulphide and sulphate minerals and even in native form (especially in volcanic regions).
  • synonyms: sulfur, S, sulphur, atomic number 16
  • hypernym: chemical element, element
  • substance holonym: sulfide, sulphide; vitriol, oil of vitriol, sulfuric acid, sulphuric acid
  • hyponym: brimstone, native sulfur, native sulphur

title: atomic number 17
titlehtml: atomic number 17
contenthtml:
noun (substance) hlor, хлор. A common nonmetallic element belonging to the halogens. Best known as a heavy yellow irritating toxic gas. Used to purify water and as a bleaching agent and disinfectant. Occurs naturally only as a salt (as in sea water).
  • synonyms: chlorine, Cl, atomic number 17
  • hypernym: chemical element, element; gas; halogen
  • substance holonym: sodium chloride, common salt
  • hyponym: radiochlorine

title: atomic number 18
titlehtml: atomic number 18
contenthtml:
noun (substance) argon, аргон. A colorless and odorless inert gas. One of the six inert gases. Comprises approximately 1% of the earth's atmosphere.
  • synonyms: argon, Ar, atomic number 18
  • hypernym: chemical element, element; noble gas, inert gas, argonon
  • substance holonym: air

title: atomic number 19
titlehtml: atomic number 19
contenthtml:
noun (substance) калий. A light soft silver-white metallic element of the alkali metal group. Oxidizes rapidly in air and reacts violently with water. Is abundant in nature in combined forms occurring in sea water and in carnallite and kainite and sylvite.
  • synonyms: potassium, K, atomic number 19
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: seawater, saltwater, brine; carnallite; kainite; langbeinite; sylvite, sylvine

title: atomic number 2
titlehtml: atomic number 2
contenthtml:
noun (substance) гелий. A very light colorless element that is one of the six inert gasses. The most difficult gas to liquefy. Occurs in economically extractable amounts in certain natural gases (as those found in Texas and Kansas).
  • synonyms: helium, He, atomic number 2
  • hypernym: chemical element, element; noble gas, inert gas, argonon

title: atomic number 21
titlehtml: atomic number 21
contenthtml:
noun (substance) скандий. A white trivalent metallic element. Sometimes classified in the rare earth group. Occurs in the Scandinavian mineral thortveitite.
  • synonyms: scandium, Sc, atomic number 21
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: thortveitite

title: atomic number 22
titlehtml: atomic number 22
contenthtml:
noun (substance) титан. A light strong grey lustrous corrosion-resistant metallic element used in strong lightweight alloys (as for airplane parts). The main sources are rutile and ilmenite.
  • synonyms: titanium, Ti, atomic number 22
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: rutile; ilmenite
  • domain of synset - topic: airplane, aeroplane, plane

title: atomic number 23
titlehtml: atomic number 23
contenthtml:
noun (substance) ванадий. A soft silvery white toxic metallic element used in steel alloys. It occurs in several complex minerals including carnotite and vanadinite.
  • synonyms: vanadium, V, atomic number 23
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: carnotite; vanadinite

title: atomic number 24
titlehtml: atomic number 24
contenthtml:
noun (substance) хром. A hard brittle multivalent metallic element. Resistant to corrosion and tarnishing.
  • synonyms: chromium, Cr, atomic number 24
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: chromite
  • hyponym: chrome

title: atomic number 25
titlehtml: atomic number 25
contenthtml:
noun (substance) марганец. A hard brittle grey polyvalent metallic element that resembles iron but is not magnetic. Used in making steel. Occurs in many minerals.
  • synonyms: manganese, Mn, atomic number 25
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: hausmannite; manganite; psilomelane; pyrolusite; rhodochrosite

title: atomic number 26
titlehtml: atomic number 26
contenthtml:
noun (substance) темир. A heavy ductile magnetic metallic element. Is silver-white in pure form but readily rusts. Used in construction and tools and armament. Plays a role in the transport of oxygen by the blood.
  • synonyms: iron, Fe, atomic number 26
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: steel; iron ore
  • hyponym: alpha iron; beta iron; gamma iron; delta iron; ingot iron; cast iron; wrought iron; galvanized iron; pig iron; scrap iron; structural iron

title: atomic number 27
titlehtml: atomic number 27
contenthtml:
noun (substance) кобальт. A hard ferromagnetic silver-white bivalent or trivalent metallic element. A trace element in plant and animal nutrition.
  • synonyms: cobalt, Co, atomic number 27
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: smaltite; cobaltite
  • hyponym: cobalt 60

title: atomic number 28
titlehtml: atomic number 28
contenthtml:
noun (substance) nikel. A hard malleable ductile silvery metallic element that is resistant to corrosion. Used in alloys. Occurs in pentlandite and smaltite and garnierite and millerite.
  • synonyms: nickel, Ni, atomic number 28
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: garnierite; millerite; pentlandite; smaltite

title: atomic number 29
titlehtml: atomic number 29
contenthtml:
noun (substance) mis, мис. A ductile malleable reddish-brown corrosion-resistant diamagnetic metallic element. Occurs in various minerals but is the only metal that occurs abundantly in large masses. Used as an electrical and thermal conductor.
  • synonyms: copper, Cu, atomic number 29
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal; conductor
  • substance holonym: brass; bronze; bornite, peacock ore; chalcocite, copper glance; chalcopyrite, copper pyrites; cuprite; malachite
  • hyponym: blister copper

title: atomic number 3
titlehtml: atomic number 3
contenthtml:
noun (substance) литий. A soft silver-white univalent element of the alkali metal group. The lightest metal known. Occurs in several minerals.
  • synonyms: lithium, Li, atomic number 3
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: lepidolite; amblygonite; spodumene; zinnwaldite

title: atomic number 30
titlehtml: atomic number 30
contenthtml:
noun (substance) rux, рух. A bluish-white lustrous metallic element. Brittle at ordinary temperatures but malleable when heated. Used in a wide variety of alloys and in galvanizing iron. It occurs naturally as zinc sulphide in zinc blende.
  • synonyms: zinc, Zn, atomic number 30
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • hyponym: spelter

title: atomic number 31
titlehtml: atomic number 31
contenthtml:
noun (substance) галлий. A rare silvery (usually trivalent) metallic element. Brittle at low temperatures but liquid above room temperature. Occurs in trace amounts in bauxite and zinc ores.
  • synonyms: gallium, Ga, atomic number 31
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: bauxite

title: atomic number 32
titlehtml: atomic number 32
contenthtml:
noun (substance) германий. A brittle grey crystalline element that is a semiconducting metalloid (resembling silicon) used in transistors. Occurs in germanite and argyrodite.
  • synonyms: germanium, Ge, atomic number 32
  • hypernym: chemical element, element; semiconductor, semiconducting material
  • substance holonym: germanite; argyrodite

title: atomic number 33
titlehtml: atomic number 33
contenthtml:
noun (substance) myşyák, мышьяк. A very poisonous metallic element that has three allotropic forms. Arsenic and arsenic compounds are used as herbicides and insecticides and various alloys. Found in arsenopyrite and orpiment and realgar.
  • synonyms: arsenic, As, atomic number 33
  • hypernym: chemical element, element
  • substance holonym: herbicide, weedkiller, weed killer; insecticide, insect powder; arsenopyrite, mispickel; orpiment; realgar

title: atomic number 34
titlehtml: atomic number 34
contenthtml:
noun (substance) селен. A toxic nonmetallic element related to sulfur and tellurium. Occurs in several allotropic forms. A stable grey metallike allotrope conducts electricity better in the light than in the dark and is used in photocells. Occurs in sulfide ores (as pyrite).
  • synonyms: selenium, Se, atomic number 34
  • hypernym: chemical element, element; antioxidant
  • substance holonym: pyrite, iron pyrite, fool's gold

title: atomic number 35
titlehtml: atomic number 35
contenthtml:
noun (substance) бром. A nonmetallic heavy volatile corrosive dark brown liquid element belonging to the halogens. Found in sea water.
  • synonyms: bromine, Br, atomic number 35
  • hypernym: chemical element, element; halogen
  • substance holonym: seawater, saltwater, brine

title: atomic number 36
titlehtml: atomic number 36
contenthtml:
noun (substance) криптон. A colorless element that is one of the six inert gasses. Occurs in trace amounts in air.
  • synonyms: krypton, Kr, atomic number 36
  • hypernym: chemical element, element; noble gas, inert gas, argonon
  • substance holonym: air

title: atomic number 37
titlehtml: atomic number 37
contenthtml:
noun (substance) рубидий. A soft silvery metallic element of the alkali metal group. Burns in air and reacts violently in water. Occurs in carnallite and lepidolite and pollucite.
  • synonyms: rubidium, Rb, atomic number 37
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: carnallite; lepidolite; pollucite

title: atomic number 38
titlehtml: atomic number 38
contenthtml:
noun (substance) стронций. A soft silver-white or yellowish metallic element of the alkali metal group. Turns yellow in air. Occurs in celestite and strontianite.
  • synonyms: strontium, Sr, atomic number 38
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: celestite; strontianite
  • hyponym: strontium 90

title: atomic number 39
titlehtml: atomic number 39
contenthtml:
noun (substance) иттрий. A silvery metallic element that is common in rare-earth minerals. Used in magnesium and aluminum alloys.
  • synonyms: yttrium, Y, atomic number 39
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: gadolinite, ytterbite; fergusonite; xenotime

title: atomic number 4
titlehtml: atomic number 4
contenthtml:
noun (substance) berilliy, бериллий. A light strong brittle grey toxic bivalent metallic element.
  • synonyms: beryllium, Be, glucinium, atomic number 4
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: beryl; chrysoberyl; gadolinite, ytterbite

title: atomic number 40
titlehtml: atomic number 40
contenthtml:
noun (substance) цирконий. A lustrous grey strong metallic element resembling titanium. It is used in nuclear reactors as a neutron absorber. It occurs in baddeleyite but is obtained chiefly from zircon.
  • synonyms: zirconium, Zr, atomic number 40
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: baddeleyite; zircon, zirconium silicate

title: atomic number 41
titlehtml: atomic number 41
contenthtml:
noun (substance) ниобий. A soft grey ductile metallic element used in alloys. Occurs in niobite. Formerly called columbium.
  • synonyms: niobium, Nb, atomic number 41
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: niobite, columbite
  • hyponym: columbium

title: atomic number 42
titlehtml: atomic number 42
contenthtml:
noun (substance) молибден. A polyvalent metallic element that resembles chromium and tungsten in its properties. Used to strengthen and harden steel.
  • synonyms: molybdenum, Mo, atomic number 42
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: molybdenite

title: atomic number 43
titlehtml: atomic number 43
contenthtml:
noun (substance) технеций. A crystalline metallic element not found in nature. Occurs as one of the fission products of uranium.
  • synonyms: technetium, Tc, atomic number 43
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal

title: atomic number 44
titlehtml: atomic number 44
contenthtml:
noun (substance) рутений. A rare polyvalent metallic element of the platinum group. It is found associated with platinum.
  • synonyms: ruthenium, Ru, atomic number 44
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal

title: atomic number 45
titlehtml: atomic number 45
contenthtml:
noun (substance) родий. A white hard metallic element that is one of the platinum group and is found in platinum ores. Used in alloys with platinum.
  • synonyms: rhodium, Rh, atomic number 45
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal

title: atomic number 46
titlehtml: atomic number 46
contenthtml:
noun (substance) палладий. A silver-white metallic element of the platinum group that resembles platinum. Occurs in some copper and nickel ores. Does not tarnish at ordinary temperatures and is used (alloyed with gold) in jewelry.
  • synonyms: palladium, Pd, atomic number 46
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal

title: atomic number 47
titlehtml: atomic number 47
contenthtml:
noun (substance) кумуш. A soft white precious univalent metallic element having the highest electrical and thermal conductivity of any metal. Occurs in argentite and in free form. Used in coins and jewelry and tableware and photography.
  • synonyms: silver, Ag, atomic number 47
  • hypernym: noble metal; conductor
  • substance holonym: sterling silver; argentite; silver
  • hyponym: coin silver

title: atomic number 48
titlehtml: atomic number 48
contenthtml:
noun (substance) кадмий. A soft bluish-white ductile malleable toxic bivalent metallic element. Occurs in association with zinc ores.
  • synonyms: cadmium, Cd, atomic number 48
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: hemimorphite, calamine

title: atomic number 49
titlehtml: atomic number 49
contenthtml:
noun (substance) индий. A rare soft silvery metallic element. Occurs in small quantities in sphalerite.
  • synonyms: indium, In, atomic number 49
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: zinc blende, blende, sphalerite

title: atomic number 5
titlehtml: atomic number 5
contenthtml:
noun (substance) bor. A trivalent metalloid element. Occurs both in a hard black crystal and in the form of a yellow or brown powder.
  • synonyms: boron, B, atomic number 5
  • hypernym: chemical element, element
  • substance holonym: kernite; borax

title: atomic number 50
titlehtml: atomic number 50
contenthtml:
noun (substance) калай. A silvery malleable metallic element that resists corrosion. Used in many alloys and to coat other metals to prevent corrosion. Obtained chiefly from cassiterite where it occurs as tin oxide.
  • synonyms: tin, Sn, atomic number 50
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: cassiterite; tinfoil, tin foil

title: atomic number 51
titlehtml: atomic number 51
contenthtml:
noun (substance) sur’ma, сурьма. A metallic element having four allotropic forms. Used in a wide variety of alloys. Found in stibnite.
  • synonyms: antimony, Sb, atomic number 51
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: stibnite

title: atomic number 52
titlehtml: atomic number 52
contenthtml:
noun (substance) теллур. A brittle silver-white metalloid element that is related to selenium and sulfur. It is used in alloys and as a semiconductor. Occurs mainly as tellurides in ores of copper and nickel and silver and gold.
  • synonyms: tellurium, Te, atomic number 52
  • hypernym: chemical element, element
  • substance holonym: telluride; sylvanite, graphic tellurium

title: atomic number 53
titlehtml: atomic number 53
contenthtml:
noun (substance) yod, йод. A nonmetallic element belonging to the halogens. Used especially in medicine and photography and in dyes. Occurs naturally only in combination in small quantities (as in sea water or rocks).
  • synonyms: iodine, iodin, I, atomic number 53
  • hypernym: chemical element, element; halogen
  • substance holonym: seawater, saltwater, brine
  • hyponym: iodine-131; iodine-125

title: atomic number 54
titlehtml: atomic number 54
contenthtml:
noun (substance) ксенон. A colorless odorless inert gaseous element occurring in the earth's atmosphere in trace amounts.
  • synonyms: xenon, Xe, atomic number 54
  • hypernym: chemical element, element; noble gas, inert gas, argonon
  • substance holonym: air

title: atomic number 55
titlehtml: atomic number 55
contenthtml:
noun (substance) цезий. A soft silver-white ductile metallic element (liquid at normal temperatures). The most electropositive and alkaline metal.
  • synonyms: cesium, caesium, Cs, atomic number 55
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: pollucite
  • hyponym: cesium 137

title: atomic number 56
titlehtml: atomic number 56
contenthtml:
noun (substance) барий. A soft silvery metallic element of the alkali earth group. Found in barite.
  • synonyms: barium, Ba, atomic number 56
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: heavy spar, barite, barytes, barium sulphate
  • hyponym: baryta

title: atomic number 57
titlehtml: atomic number 57
contenthtml:
noun (substance) лантан. A white soft metallic element that tarnishes readily. Occurs in rare earth minerals and is usually classified as a rare earth.
  • synonyms: lanthanum, La, atomic number 57
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal

title: atomic number 58
titlehtml: atomic number 58
contenthtml:
noun (substance) церий. A ductile grey metallic element of the lanthanide series. Used in lighter flints. The most abundant of the rare-earth group.
  • synonyms: cerium, Ce, atomic number 58
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: monazite; bastnasite, bastnaesite; gadolinite, ytterbite

title: atomic number 6
titlehtml: atomic number 6
contenthtml:
noun (substance) uglerod. An abundant nonmetallic tetravalent element occurring in three allotropic forms: amorphous carbon and graphite and diamond. Occurs in all organic compounds.
  • synonyms: carbon, C, atomic number 6
  • hypernym: chemical element, element
  • substance holonym: coal; petroleum, crude oil, crude, rock oil, fossil oil, oil; limestone
  • hyponym: fullerene; radiocarbon, carbon 14; char; charcoal, wood coal; carbon black, lampblack, soot, smut, crock; activated carbon, activated charcoal; graphite, black lead, plumbago; diamond, adamant

title: atomic number 60
titlehtml: atomic number 60
contenthtml:
noun (substance) неодим. A yellow trivalent metallic element of the rare earth group. Occurs in monazite and bastnasite in association with cerium and lanthanum and praseodymium.
  • synonyms: neodymium, Nd, atomic number 60
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: monazite; bastnasite, bastnaesite

title: atomic number 62
titlehtml: atomic number 62
contenthtml:
noun (substance) самарий. A grey lustrous metallic element of the rare earth group. Is used in special alloys. Occurs in monazite and bastnasite.
  • synonyms: samarium, Sm, atomic number 62
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: bastnasite, bastnaesite; monazite

title: atomic number 63
titlehtml: atomic number 63
contenthtml:
noun (substance) evropiy, европий. A bivalent and trivalent metallic element of the rare earth group.
  • synonyms: europium, Eu, atomic number 63
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: monazite

title: atomic number 64
titlehtml: atomic number 64
contenthtml:
noun (substance) гадолиний. A ductile silvery-white ductile ferromagnetic trivalent metallic element of the rare earth group.
  • synonyms: gadolinium, Gd, atomic number 64
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: gadolinite, ytterbite; samarskite

title: atomic number 65
titlehtml: atomic number 65
contenthtml:
noun (substance) тербий. A metallic element of the rare earth group. Used in lasers. Occurs in apatite and monazite and xenotime and ytterbite.
  • synonyms: terbium, Tb, atomic number 65
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: apatite; monazite; gadolinite, ytterbite

title: atomic number 66
titlehtml: atomic number 66
contenthtml:
noun (substance) disproziy, диспрозий. A trivalent metallic element of the rare earth group. Forms compounds that are highly magnetic.
  • synonyms: dysprosium, Dy, atomic number 66
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal

title: atomic number 67
titlehtml: atomic number 67
contenthtml:
noun (substance) голъмий. A trivalent metallic element of the rare earth group. Occurs together with yttrium. Forms highly magnetic compounds.
  • synonyms: holmium, Ho, atomic number 67
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: gadolinite, ytterbite

title: atomic number 69
titlehtml: atomic number 69
contenthtml:
noun (substance) тулий. A soft silvery metallic element of the rare earth group. Isotope 170 emits X-rays and is used in small portable X-ray machines. It occurs in monazite and apatite and xenotime.
  • synonyms: thulium, Tm, atomic number 69
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: apatite; monazite; xenotime

title: atomic number 70
titlehtml: atomic number 70
contenthtml:
noun (substance) иттербий. A soft silvery metallic element. A rare earth of the lanthanide series. It occurs in gadolinite and monazite and xenotime.
  • synonyms: ytterbium, Yb, atomic number 70
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: gadolinite, ytterbite; monazite; xenotime

title: atomic number 71
titlehtml: atomic number 71
contenthtml:
noun (substance) лютеций. A trivalent metallic element of the rare earth group. Usually occurs in association with yttrium.
  • synonyms: lutetium, lutecium, Lu, atomic number 71
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal

title: atomic number 72
titlehtml: atomic number 72
contenthtml:
noun (substance) гафний. A grey tetravalent metallic element that resembles zirconium chemically and is found in zirconium minerals. Used in filaments for its ready emission of electrons.
  • synonyms: hafnium, Hf, atomic number 72
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal

title: atomic number 73
titlehtml: atomic number 73
contenthtml:
noun (substance) тантал. A hard grey lustrous metallic element that is highly resistant to corrosion. Occurs in niobite and fergusonite and tantalite.
  • synonyms: tantalum, Ta, atomic number 73
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: fergusonite; niobite, columbite; tantalite

title: atomic number 74
titlehtml: atomic number 74
contenthtml:
noun (substance) vol’fram, вольфрам. A heavy grey-white metallic element. The pure form is used mainly in electrical applications. It is found in several ores including wolframite and scheelite.
  • synonyms: tungsten, wolfram, W, atomic number 74
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: scheelite; wolframite, iron manganese tungsten

title: atomic number 75
titlehtml: atomic number 75
contenthtml:
noun (substance) рений. A rare heavy polyvalent metallic element that resembles manganese chemically and is used in some alloys. Is obtained as a by-product in refining molybdenum.
  • synonyms: rhenium, Re, atomic number 75
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal

title: atomic number 76
titlehtml: atomic number 76
contenthtml:
noun (substance) осмий. A hard brittle blue-grey or blue-black metallic element that is one of the platinum metals. The heaviest metal known.
  • synonyms: osmium, Os, atomic number 76
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal

title: atomic number 77
titlehtml: atomic number 77
contenthtml:
noun (substance) иридий. A heavy brittle metallic element of the platinum group. Used in alloys. Occurs in natural alloys with platinum or osmium.
  • synonyms: iridium, Ir, atomic number 77
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal

title: atomic number 78
titlehtml: atomic number 78
contenthtml:
noun (substance) platina, платина. A heavy precious metallic element. Grey-white and resistant to corroding. Occurs in some nickel and copper ores and is also found native in some deposits.
  • synonyms: platinum, Pt, atomic number 78
  • hypernym: noble metal

title: atomic number 79
titlehtml: atomic number 79
contenthtml:
noun (substance) олтин, oltin. A soft yellow malleable ductile (trivalent and univalent) metallic element. Occurs mainly as nuggets in rocks and alluvial deposits. Does not react with most chemicals but is attacked by chlorine and aqua regia.
  • synonyms: gold, Au, atomic number 79
  • hypernym: noble metal
  • substance holonym: dental gold; sylvanite, graphic tellurium; gold foil; gold leaf; gold
  • hyponym: 24-karat gold, pure gold; gold dust; green gold; guinea gold

title: atomic number 8
titlehtml: atomic number 8
contenthtml:
noun (substance) кислород. A nonmetallic bivalent element that is normally a colorless odorless tasteless nonflammable diatomic gas. Constitutes 21 percent of the atmosphere by volume. The most abundant element in the earth's crust.

  • hypernym: chemical element, element; gas
  • substance holonym: water, H2O; air; ozone
  • hyponym: liquid oxygen, LOX

title: atomic number 80
titlehtml: atomic number 80
contenthtml:

  • synonyms: mercury, quicksilver, hydrargyrum, Hg, atomic number 80
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: cinnabar; calomel, mercurous chloride

title: atomic number 81
titlehtml: atomic number 81
contenthtml:

  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: zinc blende, blende, sphalerite

title: atomic number 82
titlehtml: atomic number 82
contenthtml:
noun (substance) кўогъшсин. A soft heavy toxic malleable metallic element. Bluish white when freshly cut but tarnishes readily to dull grey.

  • hypernym: metallic element, metal

  • hyponym: hard lead; hard lead, antimonial lead; pig lead

title: atomic number 83
titlehtml: atomic number 83
contenthtml:

  • hypernym: metallic element, metal

title: atomic number 84
titlehtml: atomic number 84
contenthtml:
noun (substance) полоний. A radioactive metallic element that is similar to tellurium and bismuth. Occurs in uranium ores but can be produced by bombarding bismuth with neutrons in a nuclear reactor.
  • synonyms: polonium, Po, atomic number 84
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal

title: atomic number 85
titlehtml: atomic number 85
contenthtml:
noun (substance) astat, астат. A highly unstable radioactive element (the heaviest of the halogen series). A decay product of uranium and thorium.
  • synonyms: astatine, At, atomic number 85
  • hypernym: chemical element, element; halogen

title: atomic number 86
titlehtml: atomic number 86
contenthtml:
noun (substance) радон. A radioactive gaseous element formed by the disintegration of radium. The heaviest of the inert gasses. Occurs naturally (especially in areas over granite) and is considered a hazard to health.
  • synonyms: radon, Rn, atomic number 86
  • hypernym: chemical element, element; noble gas, inert gas, argonon

title: atomic number 87
titlehtml: atomic number 87
contenthtml:

  • hypernym: metallic element, metal

title: atomic number 89
titlehtml: atomic number 89
contenthtml:

  • hypernym: chemical element, element
  • substance holonym: uranium ore

title: atomic number 9
titlehtml: atomic number 9
contenthtml:

  • hypernym: chemical element, element; gas; halogen
  • substance holonym: fluorite, fluorspar, fluor; fluorapatite; cryolite, Greenland spar

title: atomic number 90
titlehtml: atomic number 90
contenthtml:
noun (substance) торий. A soft silvery-white tetravalent radioactive metallic element. Isotope 232 is used as a power source in nuclear reactors. Occurs in thorite and in monazite sands.

  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: monazite; thorite
  • hyponym: thorium-228, radiothorium

titlehtml: atomic number 91
contenthtml:

  • hypernym: metallic element, metal

title: atomic number 92
titlehtml: atomic number 92
contenthtml:

  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: uraninite, pitchblende
  • hyponym: uranium 235; uranium 238

titlehtml: atomic number 93
contenthtml:

title: atomic number 94
titlehtml: atomic number 94
contenthtml:

  • hypernym: chemical element, element
  • hyponym: plutonium 239

title: atomic number 95
titlehtml: atomic number 95
contenthtml:

  • hypernym: metallic element, metal

titlehtml: atomic number 96
contenthtml:

  • synonyms: curium, Cm, atomic number 96
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal

title: atomic number 97
titlehtml: atomic number 97
contenthtml:

  • synonyms: berkelium, Bk, atomic number 97
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal

titlehtml: atomic number 98

  • hypernym: metallic element, metal

titlehtml: atomic number 99
contenthtml:

  • hypernym: metallic element, metal

titlehtml: au
contenthtml:

  • synonyms: gold, Au, atomic number 79

title: aubergine
titlehtml: aubergine
contenthtml:

  • part meronym: eggplant, aubergine, mad apple

titlehtml: australia
contenthtml:

titlehtml: austria
contenthtml:

title: xe
titlehtml: xe
contenthtml:
noun (substance) ксенон. A colorless odorless inert gaseous element occurring in the earth's atmosphere in trace amounts.
  • synonyms: xenon, Xe, atomic number 54

title: xenon
titlehtml: xenon
contenthtml:
noun (substance) ксенон. A colorless odorless inert gaseous element occurring in the earth's atmosphere in trace amounts.
  • synonyms: Xe, atomic number 54
  • hypernym: chemical element, element; noble gas, inert gas, argonon
  • substance holonym: air

title: xinjiang
titlehtml: xinjiang
contenthtml:
noun (location) Shinjong. An autonomous province in far northwestern China on the border with Mongolia and Kazakhstan. The largest province in the People's Republic of China and the homeland of the Uighur people.
  • synonyms: Xinjiang, Sinkiang, Xinjiang Uighur Autonomous Region

title: xinjiang uighur autonomous region
titlehtml: xinjiang uighur autonomous region
contenthtml:
noun (location) Shinjong. An autonomous province in far northwestern China on the border with Mongolia and Kazakhstan. The largest province in the People's Republic of China and the homeland of the Uighur people.
  • synonyms: Xinjiang, Sinkiang, Xinjiang Uighur Autonomous Region

title: xmas
titlehtml: xmas
contenthtml:
noun (time) Mavlud. A Christian holiday celebrating the birth of Christ. A quarter day in England, Wales, and Ireland.
  • synonyms: Christmas, Christmas Day, Xmas, Dec 25

title: xylophone
titlehtml: xylophone
contenthtml:
noun (artifact) ksilofon. A percussion instrument with wooden bars tuned to produce a chromatic scale and with resonators. Played with small mallets.
  • synonyms: marimba
  • hypernym: percussion instrument, percussive instrument
  • derivationally related form: xylophonist

title: y
titlehtml: y
contenthtml:
noun (substance) иттрий. A silvery metallic element that is common in rare-earth minerals. Used in magnesium and aluminum alloys.
  • synonyms: yttrium, Y, atomic number 39

title: yb
titlehtml: yb
contenthtml:
noun (substance) иттербий. A soft silvery metallic element. A rare earth of the lanthanide series. It occurs in gadolinite and monazite and xenotime.
  • synonyms: ytterbium, Yb, atomic number 70

title: year
titlehtml: year
contenthtml:
noun (time) yil. The period of time that it takes for a planet (as, e.g., Earth or Mars) to make a complete revolution around the sun.
  • hypernym: time period, period of time, period
  • hyponym: anomalistic year; solar year, tropical year, astronomical year, equinoctial year; lunar year; sidereal year
  • part meronym: month; season, time of year

title: yeast
titlehtml: yeast
contenthtml:
noun (plant) achitqi. Any of various single-celled fungi that reproduce asexually by budding or division.
  • hypernym: fungus
  • member holonym: Endomycetales, order Endomycetales
  • derivationally related form: yeasty
  • hyponym: baker's yeast, brewer's yeast, Saccharomyces cerevisiae; wine-maker's yeast, Saccharomyces ellipsoides

title: yemen
titlehtml: yemen
contenthtml:
noun (location) Yaman. A republic on the southwestern shores of the Arabian Peninsula on the Indian Ocean. Formed in 1990.
  • synonyms: Yemen, Republic of Yemen

title: yesterday
titlehtml: yesterday
contenthtml:
noun (time) kecha, kechagi. The day immediately before today.
  • hypernym: day, twenty-four hours, twenty-four hour period, 24-hour interval, solar day, mean solar day
adverb (all) kecha, kechagi. On the day preceding today.

title: yisrael
titlehtml: yisrael
contenthtml:
noun (location) Isroil. Jewish republic in southwestern Asia at eastern end of Mediterranean. Formerly part of Palestine.
  • synonyms: Israel, State of Israel, Yisrael, Zion, Sion

title: yolk
titlehtml: yolk
contenthtml:
noun (food) tuxumning sarig'i. The yellow spherical part of an egg that is surrounded by the albumen.
  • synonyms: egg yolk
  • hypernym: ingredient, fixings
  • part holonym: egg, eggs

title: young
titlehtml: young
contenthtml:
adjective (all) yosh. (used of living things especially persons) in an early period of life or development or growth.
  • synonyms: immature
  • also see: immature; junior; new
  • attribute: age
  • domain of synset - topic: living thing, animate thing
  • derivationally related form: young; youngness
  • antonym: old
  • similar to: one-year-old; two-year-old; three-year-old; four-year-old; five-year-old; adolescent, teen, teenage, teenaged; infantile; boyish, boylike, schoolboyish; childlike, childly; early; girlish, schoolgirlish; junior; little, small; newborn; preteen, preadolescent; puppyish, puppylike; tender; youngish; youthful, vernal, young

title: ytterbium
titlehtml: ytterbium
contenthtml:
noun (substance) иттербий. A soft silvery metallic element. A rare earth of the lanthanide series. It occurs in gadolinite and monazite and xenotime.

  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: gadolinite, ytterbite; monazite; xenotime

title: yttrium
titlehtml: yttrium
contenthtml:
noun (substance) иттрий. A silvery metallic element that is common in rare-earth minerals. Used in magnesium and aluminum alloys.
  • synonyms: Y, atomic number 39
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: gadolinite, ytterbite; fergusonite; xenotime

title: yugoslavia
titlehtml: yugoslavia
contenthtml:
noun (location) Serbiya va Chernogoriya. A mountainous republic in southeastern Europe bordering on the Adriatic Sea. Formed from two of the six republics that made up Yugoslavia until 1992. Serbia and Montenegro were known as the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia until 2003 when they adopted the name of the Union of Serbia and Montenegro.
  • synonyms: Serbia and Montenegro, Union of Serbia and Montenegro, Yugoslavia, Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, Jugoslavija

title: zinc
titlehtml: zinc
contenthtml:
noun (substance) rux, рух. A bluish-white lustrous metallic element. Brittle at ordinary temperatures but malleable when heated. Used in a wide variety of alloys and in galvanizing iron. It occurs naturally as zinc sulphide in zinc blende.
  • synonyms: Zn, atomic number 30
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • hyponym: spelter

title: zion
titlehtml: zion
contenthtml:
noun (location) Isroil. Jewish republic in southwestern Asia at eastern end of Mediterranean. Formerly part of Palestine.
  • synonyms: Israel, State of Israel, Yisrael, Zion, Sion

title: zirconium
titlehtml: zirconium
contenthtml:
noun (substance) цирконий. A lustrous grey strong metallic element resembling titanium. It is used in nuclear reactors as a neutron absorber. It occurs in baddeleyite but is obtained chiefly from zircon.
  • synonyms: Zr, atomic number 40
  • hypernym: metallic element, metal
  • substance holonym: baddeleyite; zircon, zirconium silicate

title: zn
titlehtml: zn
contenthtml:
noun (substance) rux, рух. A bluish-white lustrous metallic element. Brittle at ordinary temperatures but malleable when heated. Used in a wide variety of alloys and in galvanizing iron. It occurs naturally as zinc sulphide in zinc blende.
  • synonyms: zinc, Zn, atomic number 30

title: zr
titlehtml: zr
contenthtml:
noun (substance) цирконий. A lustrous grey strong metallic element resembling titanium. It is used in nuclear reactors as a neutron absorber. It occurs in baddeleyite but is obtained chiefly from zircon.
